  "local_port": 59774,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How are the types of nerve cell structured?",
  "response": "Nerve cells, also known as neurons, have a unique structure that allows them to communicate and transmit information throughout the body. There are three main types of neurons: sensory neurons, motor neurons, and interneurons. Despite their different functions, they all share a similar basic structure. \n\nA typical neuron consists of the following components:\n\n1. Cell body (soma): The cell body contains the nucleus, which holds the genetic material, and other organelles necessary for the neuron's metabolism and maintenance. It is the metabolic center of the neuron.\n\n2. Dendrites: Dendrites are short, branched extensions that emerge from the cell body. They receive and collect signals from other neurons, which are then transmitted to the cell body. The more dendrites a neuron has, the more information it can receive.\n\n3. Axon: The axon is a long, thin extension that emerges from the cell body, called the axon hillock. It is responsible for transmitting the neuron's signal, called an action potential, to other neurons or target cells, such as muscles or glands. Axons can vary in length, ranging from a few millimeters to over a meter in humans.\n\n4. Axon terminals (synaptic boutons): The axon branches out into numerous terminals at its end. These terminals form synapses, which are specialized junctions that allow the neuron to communicate with other neurons or target cells. The axon terminals contain neurotransmitters, which are chemical messengers that transmit the signal across the synapse.\n\n5. Myelin sheath: Some axons are surrounded by a fatty, insulating substance called the myelin sheath. This sheath is formed by specialized cells called oligodendrocytes in the central nervous system and Schwann cells in the peripheral nervous system. The myelin sheath speeds up the transmission of the action potential along the axon.\n\nThe structure of a neuron is essential for its function, as it allows the cell to receive, process, and transmit information throughout the nervous system.",
